</p><sec><title>Knowledge about the Pap smear</title><p>In the intervention group, the proportion of those who had heard of the Pap smear rose from 6.9% pre-intervention to 56.6% post-intervention. The difference between both groups post-intervention was found to be statistically significant (P&#x0003c;0.01) (<xref ref-type="table" rid="T2">Table 2</xref>). At baseline, less than 10% of the participants in both groups knew that the Pap smear is a test for cervical abnormalities. After the intervention, a significant proportional increase was found in those in the intervention group who knew the indication for the Pap smear (P&#x0003c;0.05) (<xref ref-type="table" rid="T3">Table 3</xref>). Despite the fact that respondents who had completed their secondary education in the intervention group constituted the greatest proportion of those aware of the Pap smear test, there was no statistically significant relationship between educational level and awareness of cervical cancer (P&#x0003e;0.05) (<xref ref-type="table" rid="T4">Table 4</xref>).</p><p>
